"""
MKT Context Commentary — Esther chapters 1–5
Run: python3 scripts/zc-context-esther-1-5.py

Source data used:
- data/interlinear/esther.json
- data/translation/draft/mediating/esther.json (MKT text)
- data/commentary/mkt-context/esther.json (ch1:v1 already present — skip)

Key decisions in this range:
- Ahasuerus = Xerxes I (486-465 BCE); third year = 483 BCE
- Haman the Agagite: deliberate Amalek/Saul typological echo (1 Sam 15)
- Mordecai's Benjaminite/Kish genealogy continues the Saul typology
- The 12-month beauty regimen reflects genuine Persian harem practice
- 10,000 talents of silver = ~375 tons, approximately 2/3 of Persia's annual revenue
- The golden scepter scene (5:2): Persian court protocol confirmed by Herodotus
- ch1:v1 is already present in the output file — script skips it via merge_comm
"""

import json, pathlib

ROOT = pathlib.Path(__file__).parent.parent

def load_comm(source, book):
    p = ROOT / 'data' / 'commentary' / source / f'{book}.json'
    if p.exists():
        return json.loads(p.read_text())
    return {}

def save_comm(source, book, data):
    p = ROOT / 'data' / 'commentary' / source / f'{book}.json'
    p.parent.mkdir(parents=True, exist_ok=True)
    p.write_text(json.dumps(data, ensure_ascii=False, indent=None))
    print(f'  wrote {p.relative_to(ROOT)}')

def merge_comm(existing, new_data):
    """Merge new_data into existing without overwriting present entries."""
    for ch, verses in new_data.items():
        if ch not in existing:
            existing[ch] = {}
        for v, html in verses.items():
            if v not in existing[ch]:
                existing[ch][v] = html

EST15 = {
    "1": {
        "2": "<p>The <strong>citadel of Susa</strong> (<em>šûšan habbîrāh</em>) was the winter palace of the Achaemenid kings, located in what is now southwestern Iran (ancient Elam). Archaeological excavations since 1885 have uncovered the Apadana (audience hall) and throne room complex at Susa; the column bases and glazed-tile decorations match the book's description of luxury. 'On his royal throne' uses Persian court ceremonial language: the king seated on the throne was the ritual center of cosmic order in Achaemenid ideology.</p>",
        "3": "<p>The third year of Xerxes I was 483 BCE — immediately before his ill-fated campaign against Greece (the battles of Thermopylae and Salamis, 480 BCE). The <strong>banquet for all his princes and officials</strong> likely served political and military purposes: Herodotus (7.8) records Xerxes convening a council of Persian nobles to plan the Greek expedition at approximately this time. The military commanders (<em>ḥêl pāras ûmāḏay</em>, literally 'the army of Persia and Media') were the core of imperial power; the 180-day banquet was partly a prolonged military muster.</p>",
        "4": "<p>The <strong>180-day display</strong> of the kingdom's 'splendid wealth and glorious honor' matches Herodotus's descriptions of Persian court magnificence. Persian royal ideology presented the king as the representative of Ahura Mazda ('Wise Lord') — his wealth was not merely personal but cosmic: the riches of all nations flowing to the divine center. The Persepolis treasury tablets document the enormous concentration of silver and gold at the Persian court. The sustained display served to impress vassals, intimidate enemies, and demonstrate that the Persian order was the natural order of the world.</p>",
        "5": "<p>The <strong>seven-day banquet for all the people of Susa</strong> — from the greatest to the least — is a deliberately populist act: the king's generosity extended to the entire city, not just the nobility. The citadel (<em>bîrāh</em>) housed the palace complex, while Susa proper was the surrounding city. This distinction between the citadel and the city appears throughout the book (Neh 1:1 uses the same term for the citadel Nehemiah served from). The banquet in the enclosed garden reflects the Persian <em>pairidaeza</em> (paradise = royal garden), the origin of the English word 'paradise.'</p>",
        "6": "<p>The detailed description of the <strong>decorations</strong> — white and violet linen curtains, silver rings in marble columns, couches of gold and silver on a mosaic pavement of colored stones — matches the extravagance of the Persepolis reliefs and surviving tile fragments from Susa. Linen hangings of white and blue/violet on marble are attested in Persian palace archaeology. The marble floor (<em>rīṣpaṯ bāhat wāšēš wəḏar wəsōḥāreṯ</em> — four types of precious stone) is consistent with Achaemenid palace construction at Susa as described in the Susa foundation inscription of Darius I.</p>",
        "7": "<p>The golden goblets 'each one different from the others' are a detail of Persian royal hospitality attested in Herodotus and in the Persepolis fortification texts: the king's table service consisted of unique vessels rather than matching sets, signaling individualized royal attention. <strong>Royal wine flowing freely</strong> (<em>yayin malkûṯ rāḇ</em>) — wine was central to Persian elite culture; the Persepolis fortification texts record wine allocations to workers and nobles in enormous quantities. Persian royal wine was a prized commodity distributed as a mark of favor.</p>",
        "8": "<p>The instruction that <strong>no one was compelled</strong> — 'each man could drink as he pleased' — is a pointed social observation. Persian banquets typically had an official cup-bearer who controlled the flow of wine; this banquet suspended that control as a royal gift. The suspension of compulsion was itself a form of royal generosity — the ultimate gift from a despotic monarchy was the freedom to choose. The irony is that the entire chapter concerns compulsion: Vashti will shortly be compelled to appear and then compelled to leave.</p>",
        "9": "<p><strong>Queen Vashti held a separate banquet for the women</strong> in the royal palace. Persian court protocol required strict gender segregation in official settings — the women's quarters (<em>bêṯ hannāšîm</em>) were physically separated from the men's court. Vashti's banquet is noted only to establish her presence in the palace complex and to set up the contrast with her refusal to appear at the men's banquet. The existence of a separate women's banquet implies Vashti had her own sphere of authority and social prestige within the court.</p>",
        "10": "<p>The <strong>seven eunuchs</strong> (<em>sārîsîm</em>, H5631) who served before the king held positions of significant power in the Persian court. Eunuchs were trusted personal servants precisely because they had no family-dynasty interests; they served as chamberlains, messengers, and custodians of the royal household. Herodotus names Xerxes' trusted eunuch Natacas; the Persepolis fortification texts document the palace eunuchs' administrative roles. The 'seventh day' when the king's heart was 'high with wine' sets up the scene as a court decision made under compromised judgment.</p>",
        "11": "<p>The command to bring Vashti 'wearing the royal crown (<em>keter malkûṯ</em>), to display her beauty' has generated debate: did it mean appearing in only the crown, or appearing with the crown among other clothing? The Hebrew is ambiguous. Most scholars read it as a summons to appear before the assembled men — the display of the queen as a trophy of the king's wealth and power, parallel to the 180-day display of wealth (v4). The rabbinic reading (appearing only in the crown) may overread, but both readings agree the summons was about the king's display of possession.</p>",
        "12": "<p>Vashti's <strong>refusal</strong> (<em>wattəmāʾēn hammalkāh waštî lābôʾ</em>) is brief and unexplained — the most enigmatic act in the book. The text gives no reason. The king's 'furious anger' (<em>qāṣap hammelek məʾōḏ waḥămaṯô bāʿărāh bô</em>) uses the same vocabulary as Pharaoh's anger at his servants (Gen 40:2) — a court anger that reconfigures fates. The narrative silence about Vashti's motivation is theologically deliberate: the book's theological method is the appearance of coincidence, and the chain begins here.</p>",
        "13": "<p>The <strong>wise men who understood the law</strong> (<em>yōḏəʿê ḥaʿittîm</em>) were the court jurists and astrologers — a standard category in ancient courts (cf. Gen 41:8; Dan 2:2). Persian administrative procedure required consulting legal experts before royal decisions affecting court protocol. The phrase 'those closest to him' identifies the inner circle of seven noble families — the same seven mentioned in Herodotus (3.84) who had special access rights to the king established by Darius I: they could approach the king without prior summons.</p>",
        "14": "<p>The seven advisers — Carshena, Shethar, Admatha, Tarshish, Meres, Marsena, and <strong>Memucan</strong> — are all Persian names, several of which can be compared with Persian onomastic records. The 'seven princes of Persia and Media' who had the right to 'see the king's face' was a constitutional feature of the Persian monarchy: Herodotus (3.84) records that Darius I granted the six co-conspirators who helped him seize power the right of unrestricted royal access. This inner circle could approach the king without prior summons — a privilege otherwise subject to the same scepter rule Esther faces in ch. 4.</p>",
        "15": "<p>The formal legal question — 'What must be done with Queen Vashti, because she has not obeyed the command of King Ahasuerus?' — frames Vashti's refusal as a legal matter, not merely a domestic dispute. Persian royal command had the force of irrevocable law; disobedience was by definition a criminal act. The queen's status as wife did not provide immunity: the king and the queen were not equals in Persian law, but sovereign and subject. The consultation with legal advisers before punishment was a form of procedural legitimacy rather than genuine deliberation.</p>",
        "16": "<p>Memucan's argument escalates: Vashti's disobedience will spread 'to all women' throughout the empire, causing domestic insubordination at every level. This is a court counselor manipulating the king's anger for political ends. The concern is not about marriage ethics but about social order: Persian imperial ideology required hierarchical obedience from the household level upward. A queen's disobedience was a threat to cosmic order in Persian court ideology, where the king's household mirrored the divine hierarchy.</p>",
        "17": "<p>The fear that women throughout the empire will 'despise their husbands' reflects the Persian court's anxiety about domestic hierarchy as the foundation of political order. Memucan's prediction that every woman in the empire will hear of Vashti's act and emulate it is hyperbole for political effect, but it reflects real anxieties about social contagion in hierarchical societies. The nobles' self-interest is also at stake: their own domestic authority would be challenged if the queen's example spread.</p>",
        "18": "<p>The 'noblewomen of Persia and Media' hearing of Vashti's conduct introduces the possibility of elite female solidarity — a genuine concern in courts where royal women wielded informal power. The Persepolis fortification tablets document that royal women (including the queen mother and king's wives) held land grants and controlled significant economic resources. Memucan's argument appeals to the nobles' self-interest: their own domestic authority was at stake if powerful women followed Vashti's example.</p>",
        "19": "<p>The <strong>laws of the Persians and Medes that cannot be altered</strong> (<em>dāṯ-pāras ûmāḏay</em>) is a constitutional principle confirmed throughout the book (8:8; Dan 6:8, 12, 15). Once issued, a Persian royal decree was irreversible — the king could not rescind his own law, only issue a counter-decree. This constitutional feature is the engine of the book's plot: Haman's decree against the Jews (ch. 3) cannot be cancelled, only countered by a second decree authorizing Jewish self-defense (ch. 8). The irrevocability of Persian law is the trap within which all the characters must maneuver.</p>",
        "20": "<p>'All wives will give honor to their husbands, from the greatest to the least' — the decree addresses household order across all 127 provinces in a single imperial act. This is the Persian empire's administrative capacity applied to domestic ethics. The decree illustrates both the reach of Persian imperial administration (letters to every province, v22) and the absurdity of legislating domestic honor: honor cannot be compelled by royal decree. The very attempt reveals the fragility of the hierarchy it tries to enforce.</p>",
        "21": "<p>The king's ready acceptance of Memucan's advice reveals Ahasuerus as a king easily directed by his advisers. This pattern repeats throughout the book: Ahasuerus gives Haman his signet ring (3:10), accepts Haman's advice to destroy the Jews without investigating (3:11), then reverses course equally quickly when Esther and Mordecai petition him (8:1–12). His passivity and manipulability is the narrative condition that makes both Haman's plot and Esther's counter-plot possible.</p>",
        "22": "<p>The letters 'to each province in its own script and to each people in their own language' is precisely what the Persepolis fortification tablets and the Behistun inscription demonstrate: Darius I issued the Behistun inscription in Old Persian, Elamite, and Babylonian simultaneously. The Persian imperial administration operated in multiple languages across its vast territory. The final phrase about the husband's language being the household standard also likely indicates that the husband's native tongue governed domestic affairs — a linguistic dimension of household authority.</p>"
    },
    "2": {
        "1": "<p>The opening of ch. 2 — 'when King Ahasuerus's anger had cooled, he thought of Vashti' — captures a characteristic Persian court dynamic: decisions made in anger are followed by regret. The phrase 'what she had done and <strong>what had been decreed against her</strong>' (<em>mâ-niḡzar ʿālêhā</em>) acknowledges the irreversibility of the Persian legal system: the king cannot un-decree Vashti's removal even if he wishes to. The gap between his desire (to recall Vashti) and legal impossibility (the decree is irrevocable) creates the narrative opening for Esther to enter.</p>",
        "2": "<p>The attendants' suggestion to seek beautiful young women was a standard Persian harem-expansion procedure. Herodotus (9.108) describes Xerxes' pursuit of women throughout his court; the fortification tablets document 'harim women' among those receiving rations from the palace stores. The initiative comes from the attendants — again, the king is passive, moved by others. 'Beautiful young women' (<em>nāʿărôṯ bəṯûlôṯ ṭôḇôṯ marʾeh</em>) specifies unmarried virgins — the harem required women of unquestionable status.</p>",
        "3": "<p>The appointment of commissioners throughout all provinces to gather young women was effectively a sexual conscription. This was not a competition young women chose to enter: they were 'gathered' (<em>qāḇaṣ</em>, H6908 — to collect, assemble). The women were brought to Susa and placed under the custody of Hegai, the eunuch in charge of the women — removed from their families permanently. The <strong>harem</strong> (<em>bêṯ hannāšîm</em>, 'house of the women') at Susa has been partially excavated; it was a self-contained residential and administrative complex within the palace.</p>",
        "4": "<p>'The young woman who pleases the king become queen in place of Vashti' — the selection process was entirely based on royal pleasure and physical attraction. The plan pleased the king (<em>wayyîṭaḇ haddāḇār bəʿênê hammelek</em>) — this formula of royal pleasure appears repeatedly in the book to mark decisions that advance the plot regardless of their ethical ambiguity. The narrator never moralizes about the harem system; it is presented as the political reality within which God's people must survive.</p>",
        "5": "<p>Mordecai's genealogy — son of Jair, son of Shimei, son of Kish, a Benjaminite — is deliberately loaded. <strong>Kish</strong> was the father of King Saul (1 Sam 9:1); <strong>Shimei son of Gera</strong> was the Benjaminite who cursed David during Absalom's revolt (2 Sam 16:5–13). The genealogy places Mordecai in the royal Benjaminite line and introduces the Saul-Amalek typology that runs through the whole book: as Saul was the Benjaminite king who failed to destroy Agag (1 Sam 15), Mordecai is the Benjaminite who will confront Haman the Agagite — the crisis Saul's disobedience left unresolved.</p>",
        "6": "<p>Mordecai 'had been carried into exile from Jerusalem among those taken captive with King <strong>Jeconiah</strong> (Jehoiachin) of Judah' — the first deportation, 597 BCE (2 Kgs 24:10–16), about 115 years before the events of the book. The reference to Jeconiah is significant: he is in the Davidic royal line (Matt 1:11–12). The Babylonian exile records include a tablet documenting rations for 'Yaukin king of the land of Yahudu' (Jehoiachin) at Babylon — placing the exile of Mordecai's family in documented historical context.</p>",
        "7": "<p><strong>Hadassah</strong> (Hebrew, 'myrtle') — <strong>Esther</strong> (Persian, likely from <em>stāra</em> 'star' or possibly related to Babylonian Ishtar) — embodied the double-identity that characterized Jewish diaspora life: a Hebrew name for use within the community, a Persian name for public life. Myrtle was a symbol of beauty and peace in Jewish tradition (Zech 1:8, 11; Neh 8:15). Mordecai's adoption of his orphaned cousin mirrors Boaz's protection of Ruth — both stories center on a male protector enabling a woman's entry into an alien power structure for the community's salvation.</p>",
        "8": "<p>Esther's entry into the harem — 'when the king's command and decree became known and many young women were gathered' — uses passive construction: Esther was gathered, not choosing to present herself. She was taken. The verb <em>lāqaḥ</em> (to take) in v8 is the same used for taking a wife — the harem entry was linguistically indistinguishable from marriage. Hegai's oversight of the harem is confirmed in Persian administrative sources: the harem superintendent was among the most powerful palace officials, responsible for both security and the management of enormous resources.</p>",
        "9": "<p>Esther 'won his favor' (<em>wattīśāʾ ḥeseḏ lĕphānāyw</em>) — the term <em>ḥeseḏ</em> (H2617, steadfast love/favor) appears here in a purely relational/social sense. The same term describes God's covenant love throughout the OT; in Esther, it operates as human favor whose divine source is never named. Hegai's quick provision of 'her prescribed beauty treatments and her portions' and seven serving women represents preferential treatment — suggesting that Esther's charm and intelligence were as much the cause of her advancement as her physical beauty.</p>",
        "10": "<p>Esther's concealment of her Jewish identity on Mordecai's instruction is the book's first instance of the diaspora survival strategy of passing: operating within a dominant culture without revealing one's full identity. This practice has parallels throughout Jewish diaspora history and is never condemned in the narrative — it is presented as prudent self-protection in a potentially hostile environment. The instruction is revisited at 2:20 and eventually overturned in 4:16 when Esther reveals her identity at mortal risk. The tension between concealment and disclosure structures the narrative.</p>",
        "11": "<p>Mordecai 'walked back and forth before the courtyard of the harem every day' — a detail that establishes his ongoing care for Esther and his spatial proximity to the palace. The harem courtyard was accessible to the public in its outer reaches; walking there was not restricted. This daily surveillance also establishes Mordecai as a regular presence near the king's gate (v19, 21; 3:2–3), which was a legitimate location for minor officials and petitioners. The king's gate was where lower-level royal servants conducted public business.</p>",
        "12": "<p>The <strong>twelve-month beauty preparation</strong> — six months with oil of myrrh, six months with spices and cosmetics — reflects genuine Persian harem practice. The Persepolis fortification tablets record large allocations of oil and cosmetics for 'the women of the palace.' Myrrh (<em>môr</em>) was used in anointing oil (Exod 30:23) and in love poetry (Song 1:13; 5:5) — its application for a year of preparation reflects both luxury and the ritual purification parallel to consecration. Each woman had only one chance before the king; the prolonged preparation reflected the investment in that single opportunity.</p>",
        "13": "<p>Each woman could take 'whatever she chose' from the harem to the king's chamber — meaning clothing, jewelry, or attending servants. This choice was significant: a well-advised choice could enhance presentation and demonstrate intelligence; a poor choice could signal poor judgment. Esther's choice (v15 — she took 'nothing except what Hegai recommended') showed wisdom: she deferred to the expert rather than displaying independent judgment that might not align with the king's tastes. The strategic self-effacement that would characterize her entire approach was already present.</p>",
        "14": "<p>Women who had been with the king returned 'to the second harem, under the care of Shaashgaz, the king's eunuch who attended the concubines.' This reveals that women who had been with the king were permanently reclassified as concubines — permanently housed in the palace but no longer eligible for the bridal competition. They were not returned to their families. Only those summoned by name would see the king again. This social reality — women permanently removed from their communities — is the backdrop against which Esther's story unfolds.</p>",
        "15": "<p>Esther 'won the approval of everyone who saw her' (<em>wattīśāʾ ḥeseḏ bəʿênê kol-rōʾehā</em>) — the same formula as v9 (Hegai's favor). The repeated formula signals a pattern: Esther systematically wins the favor of every gatekeeper she encounters through the book. She did not assert herself but deferred: 'she asked for nothing except what Hegai recommended' — a posture of apparent passivity that actually demonstrated superior intelligence (trusting the local expert over her own instincts). The phrase 'daughter of Abihail the uncle of Mordecai, who had adopted her' formally identifies Esther's legal status.</p>",
        "16": "<p>Esther was taken to Ahasuerus 'in the tenth month — the month of Tebeth — in his seventh year' = 479 BCE, immediately after the failed Greek campaign. Xerxes returned from Greece (479 BCE) to his court at Susa, where the Esther events are set. The timing is historically plausible. The year-long harem preparation (v12) placed her entry after the Greek defeat, when Xerxes' court needed consolation and the king was emotionally vulnerable — a convergence of historical plausibility and narrative providence.</p>",
        "17": "<p>The king 'loved Esther more than all the other women' and she won 'grace and favor' (<em>ḥeseḏ wāraḥamîm</em>) beyond all the others. The doubled noun — <em>ḥeseḏ</em> (covenant love/favor) and <em>raḥamîm</em> (compassion) — echoes the language of divine covenantal affection. In Exod 34:6 and throughout the Psalms, God is described as abounding in <em>ḥeseḏ</em> and <em>raḥamîm</em>. The narrator applies this divine-love vocabulary to the king's feeling for Esther — a subtle signal that the hidden God is operating through this 'coincidental' royal preference.</p>",
        "18": "<p>'Esther's banquet' — a <strong>ḥag</strong> (H2282, feast/festival) given in Esther's honor — and a <strong>release</strong> (<em>hanaḥāh</em>, tax remission or rest from labor obligations) for the provinces were standard Persian royal gestures of celebration. Persian kings marked significant events with distributions of royal favor: remission of taxes, gifts to provinces, release from tribute — gestures that secured loyalty. The 'distribution of gifts according to the king's bounty' parallels Persian royal generosity attested in the Persepolis fortification texts where rations and gifts were distributed at festivals.</p>",
        "19": "<p>'When the young women were gathered a second time, Mordecai was sitting at the king's gate.' The second gathering of young women is unexplained — possibly a harem expansion or review; the detail is included to place Mordecai at the gate at the time of the conspiracy that follows. Sitting at the king's gate was the position of minor officials and courtiers in the Persian administrative system; Neh 2:8 uses the same spatial language. Mordecai's regular presence there provided him with information about court activities — it was the ancient equivalent of an outer-court civil-service post.</p>",
        "20": "<p>The repetition of the concealment instruction — 'Esther still had not disclosed her family background or nationality, just as Mordecai had instructed her, for Esther obeyed Mordecai just as when she was under his care' — emphasizes both her continued obedience and her unusual situation: she was queen of the empire while maintaining a secret identity. The phrase 'as when she was under his care' implies that even in the palace, she still deferred to Mordecai — an unusual authority structure that will be tested and ultimately inverted in ch. 4.</p>",
        "21": "<p>Bigthan and Teresh's plot to assassinate the king — while Mordecai was sitting at the king's gate — is the 'accidental' intelligence coup that will save Mordecai's life in ch. 6. How did Mordecai overhear a palace assassination plot? The king's gate was a genuine administrative center where many people passed; gate officials heard things. The two eunuchs guarded the threshold (<em>šōmərê hassap</em>) — a specific position controlling access to the royal apartments. Their position gave them both access and grievance (eunuchs sometimes led palace coups in ancient courts).</p>",
        "22": "<p>Mordecai 'reported it to Queen Esther, and Esther told the king, giving Mordecai credit' (<em>wattōʾmer ʾestēr lammelek bəšēm mordəḵay</em>). The chain — Mordecai → Esther → king, with credit attributed correctly — is the first instance of Esther functioning as an intermediary between Mordecai and the king, the role she will play at personal risk in chs. 4–9. The careful attribution of credit to Mordecai ('in Mordecai's name') establishes the unrewarded-good-deed that becomes crucial when the king cannot sleep in ch. 6.</p>",
        "23": "<p>The recording of the conspiracy 'in the Book of the Chronicles in the presence of the king' (<em>sēpher diḇrê hayyāmîm</em>) is the administrative act that becomes the hinge of the plot. Persian administrative practice required all significant court events to be documented in the royal daybooks. Herodotus (8.85, 90) mentions Xerxes having scribes record acts of valor in battle. This seemingly routine administrative note is the most consequential 'coincidence' in the book: the recorded deed will be read to the sleepless king at exactly the moment Haman arrives to request Mordecai's execution.</p>"
    },
    "3": {
        "1": "<p><strong>Haman the son of Hammedatha the Agagite</strong> — the Agagite identification is the book's most loaded genealogical notice. Agag was the king of the Amalekites whom Saul was commanded to kill (1 Sam 15:2–3) but spared in disobedience; Samuel killed Agag himself (1 Sam 15:33). Haman's Agagite identity is almost certainly a literary signal: the Amalek-Israel conflict, which began with the attack on Israel in the wilderness (Exod 17:8–16; Deut 25:17–19) and which Saul failed to resolve, is being resumed. The Amalekite and Benjaminite lines face off again — with Mordecai having the opportunity Saul refused.</p>",
        "2": "<p>The royal command to bow to Haman placed Mordecai in direct conflict with Persian court protocol. <strong>Bowing</strong> before powerful figures was standard in the ancient Near East and was not necessarily idolatrous — Esther herself will bow before Ahasuerus (8:3). Mordecai's refusal may reflect a specific objection to bowing before an Amalekite enemy of Israel rather than a general refusal of prostration. The text never explains his refusal; it merely notes it and records the escalating consequences. Ancient Jewish interpretation supplied the Amalekite reasoning (connecting Exod 17:14–16 with Haman's ancestry).</p>",
        "3": "<p>The king's servants asked Mordecai 'Why do you disobey the king's command?' — making his refusal not merely a personal slight to Haman but a violation of royal decree. This is important: Mordecai's act was not private religious scruple but public civil disobedience of an explicit royal order. The servants' repeated questioning ('day after day') shows they tried to resolve it at the lowest level before escalating. Their eventual report to Haman — mentioning that Mordecai had told them he was a Jew — suggests Mordecai himself had explained his refusal in ethnic/religious terms.</p>",
        "4": "<p>Mordecai 'had told them he was a Jew' (<em>higgîḏ lāhem kî-hûʾ yəhûḏî</em>) — here, voluntarily, in contrast to Esther's concealment of her identity. The disclosure to the servants who challenged him was likely Mordecai's explanation for his refusal. This voluntary disclosure contrasts sharply with Esther's ongoing concealment, raising the question of whether one or the other strategy was right. The book refuses to resolve this tension, presenting both as responses to the same threat from different positions in the power structure.</p>",
        "5": "<p>Haman's rage — 'Haman was filled with rage' (<em>wayyimlāʾ hāmān ḥēmāh</em>) — is the emotional center of the book's plot. The vocabulary of rage (<em>ḥēmāh</em>, burning anger) echoes the king's anger at Vashti (1:12, same word). Both the king and Haman act from identical emotional impulses; the difference is that the king's anger led to replacing one woman with another, while Haman's anger will lead to genocide. The disproportion between offence (one man's refusal to bow) and response (exterminating an entire people) characterizes Haman as a tyrant whose personal insult generates mass violence.</p>",
        "6": "<p>'It seemed beneath him to lay hands on Mordecai alone' — Haman's decision to extend retaliation from one man to an entire people reflects ethnic-totalizing logic: Mordecai represents his people, so the people must be punished collectively for one man's act. This logic has recurred throughout history in programs of ethnic persecution: the collective responsibility principle that made genocide the 'solution' to individual provocation. The phrase 'for they had told him what people Mordecai belonged to' shows that Mordecai's Jewish identity was the trigger for collective punishment rather than individual execution.</p>",
        "7": "<p>The <strong>Pur</strong> (lot, Persian loanword) cast in Nisan to determine the month of destruction is the origin of the festival name Purim (9:26). Casting lots to determine auspicious times was standard in the ancient Near East; the Babylonian calendar was governed by astrological omens, and the Persians also consulted omens for major undertakings. The lot fell on Adar — the 12th month — giving Haman (and the Jews) nearly a year between the decree (3:13) and the execution date. This eleven-month gap is what makes Esther's intervention possible.</p>",
        "8": "<p>Haman's speech to Ahasuerus is a masterpiece of manipulation: 'a certain people scattered and dispersed throughout all the provinces of your kingdom, whose laws are different (<em>šōnôṯ</em>) from those of every other people, and who do not keep the king's laws.' Three charges: (1) a diaspora people without a territorial power base; (2) cultural distinctiveness from the majority; (3) alleged civil disobedience. These charges constitute the classical template of antisemitic accusation across history — foreignness, legal non-conformity, and disloyalty — without a single piece of evidence.</p>",
        "9": "<p>The offer of <strong>10,000 talents of silver</strong> to the royal treasury is an enormous sum. The annual revenue of the Achaemenid empire was approximately 15,000 talents; Haman's offer represented about 2/3 of annual imperial income. Herodotus (3.95) records Persian provincial tribute at 7,740 silver talents annually. Haman likely anticipated seizing the assets of the destroyed Jewish communities (the decree, 3:13, authorized plunder). The king's casual response — 'the silver is yours' (3:11) — suggests he was already wealthy enough to dismiss it or did not expect collection.</p>",
        "10": "<p>The king removed his <strong>signet ring</strong> (<em>ṭabbaʿaṯ</em>, H2885) and gave it to Haman — the most complete transfer of executive authority possible in the Persian system. The signet ring was the seal of royal command: documents sealed with it carried the authority of the king himself. This act is paralleled by Pharaoh giving his ring to Joseph (Gen 41:42) — but in reversed valence: Pharaoh's gift enabled salvation; Ahasuerus's gift enables genocide. The same administrative gesture serves opposite ends depending on the character of the recipient.</p>",
        "11": "<p>'The silver is yours, and the people also — do with them as you see fit' (<em>kəṭôḇ bəʿêneḵā laʿăśôṯ bām</em>) — the king gives both the money and the people to Haman. The casual dismissal reveals a king who has not investigated the charge, demanded evidence, considered the economic impact of eliminating a productive segment of the population, or consulted with advisers. The same passivity that characterized his reaction to Vashti and his acceptance of the beauty-pageant plan now hands an entire people's fate to one man's personal grievance.</p>",
        "12": "<p>The royal scribes summoned on the 13th of Nisan — the day before Passover — to write the destruction decree creates a bitter irony: on the eve of the festival celebrating Israel's first deliverance from a great empire, the empire issues a new destruction order. The letters were written 'exactly as Haman had commanded' in every province's own script and language — the same multilingual administrative reach used for Vashti's decree (1:22), now deployed for genocide.</p>",
        "13": "<p>The decree called for the <strong>'destruction, killing, and annihilation'</strong> (<em>ləhašmîḏ leharōg ûləʾabbēḏ</em>) of 'all the Jews — young and old, women and children' on the 13th of Adar. The triple verb 'destroy, kill, annihilate' is the same formula used in 8:11 when the counter-decree authorizes Jewish self-defense. The symmetry is deliberate: the counter-decree uses identical language, authorizing the same violence against attackers that the original decree authorized against the Jews.</p>",
        "14": "<p>The decree 'to be issued as law in every province' — publicly posted, legally binding, in every administrative unit — made this a formal legal action, not a private pogrom. The public nature of the decree was both a bureaucratic necessity (provincial administrators needed legal authorization to act) and a psychological weapon: the Jews knew about it and had eleven months to contemplate their destruction. The Adar date was chosen by lot (3:7) — providence operating through pagan divination to set a date late enough to allow intervention.</p>",
        "15": "<p>'The couriers rode out under urgent royal orders, and the decree was issued in the citadel of Susa. <strong>While the king and Haman sat down to drink, the city of Susa was bewildered</strong> (<em>wəhāʿîr šûšan nāḇôḵāh</em>).' The contrast is devastating: the two architects of genocide settle in for a drinking session while the city they govern is thrown into confusion. The Susa population was not entirely composed of those who hated Jews — many had Jewish neighbors and business associates. The rulers' indifference to the social disruption they cause is a moral indictment embedded without commentary.</p>"
    },
    "4": {
        "1": "<p>Mordecai's response to the decree — <strong>tearing his clothes, putting on sackcloth and ashes, going out into the city crying aloud with a bitter cry</strong> — follows standard mourning protocol (Gen 37:34; 2 Sam 3:31; Job 2:12; Jon 3:6). The ritual actions were not merely expressions of grief but acts of public lamentation that activated social solidarity: public mourning was a recognized form of community protest and appeal for divine intervention. The sackcloth prevented Mordecai from entering the palace gate (v2) — the sanctified space of royal administration could not be entered in a state of mourning contamination.</p>",
        "2": "<p>Mordecai 'came as far as the entrance of the king's gate, for no one was permitted to enter the king's gate wearing sackcloth' — the same gate where he had worked (2:19, 21; 3:2) was now closed to him in his mourning. The prohibition on mourning attire in the royal precinct was widespread in the ancient Near East: Neh 2:1–2 records Nehemiah's fear when his mourning face was noticed before the king. The palace was required to present an image of order and prosperity; visible grief threatened that image and was therefore prohibited.</p>",
        "3": "<p>'In every province where the king's command and decree arrived, there was <strong>great mourning among the Jews — fasting, weeping, and wailing; many lay in sackcloth and ashes</strong>.' The communal response across the diaspora demonstrates that Jewish communal networks functioned across the empire's vast extent. News traveled through the Persian administrative infrastructure (the royal road system covered 1,700 miles from Susa to Sardis) and through Jewish community networks. The mourning, fasting, and sackcloth were simultaneously grief, intercession, and solidarity across geographical distance.</p>",
        "4": "<p>Esther's distress at hearing of Mordecai's mourning — and her sending of garments to clothe him (so he could approach the gate) — reveals the limits of her information and her priority: she wanted him to be able to communicate with her, not merely to alleviate his grief. The garments represent an attempt to restore normality for communication; Mordecai refused them, insisting on the visible mourning that communicated the gravity of the crisis. The tension between Esther's instinct to manage appearances and Mordecai's insistence on visible truth characterizes their different positions in the power structure.</p>",
        "5": "<p>Esther summoned Hatach, 'one of the king's eunuchs assigned to attend her' — indicating that Esther had personal attendants who could move between the harem and the outer court. The harem was not a prison (residents could send and receive messengers) but was physically and socially isolated from the normal male court. Hatach functioned as Esther's external proxy — the mechanism by which a woman in the harem could communicate with a man in the public outer court, both of which were parts of the same palace complex but governed by different access rules.</p>",
        "6": "<p>The city square (<em>rĕḥôḇ hāʿîr</em>) in front of the king's gate was the main public space of Susa — the place where merchants, petitioners, and civil servants transacted public business. Mordecai's positioning there in sackcloth was a deliberate public statement: visible in the main civic space, creating an unavoidable scene in symbolic sight of the palace. The choice of the most public location available amplified his mourning into public protest and ensured that word would reach Esther through multiple channels.</p>",
        "7": "<p>Mordecai told Hatach 'everything that had happened to him, including the <strong>precise sum of money Haman had offered to deposit in the royal treasury</strong>.' The detail about the money is legally significant: it established that the decree was not purely political but financially motivated, with Haman personally profiting from Jewish property confiscation. This information gave Esther — and eventually the king — grounds to oppose the decree on fiscal and legal grounds. Haman's financial stake in the genocide made his conflict of interest legally actionable.</p>",
        "8": "<p>Mordecai gave Hatach 'a copy of the written edict issued in Susa for their destruction, to show Esther and explain it to her.' The physical document was both evidence and a legal instrument. Esther needed to see the actual decree rather than a secondhand summary: Persian court procedure required documentary evidence for petitions to the king, and Esther would need to know the precise legal language of the decree to formulate a counter-petition. Mordecai's instruction to 'urge her to go in to the king and implore his favor' set the stage for Esther's pivotal decision.</p>",
        "9": "<p>The messenger chain — Hatach relaying between Mordecai in the public square and Esther in the harem — represents the gap between two worlds: the public world of danger and the private world of privilege. Esther in the palace was insulated from the reality of the decree — she had not heard it; it had not yet penetrated the harem's comfortable isolation. The messengers carry not just information but the imperative that Esther's two worlds must now collide. Her comfortable separation from the crisis she has been spared is itself part of what makes her the right person to intervene.</p>",
        "10": "<p>Esther's reply to Mordecai through Hatach reveals her self-understanding as still bound by palace protocol even in a crisis. She 'spoke to Hatach and sent him back to Mordecai with this message' — she was reasoning through the problem and communicating the legal constraint before accepting the mission. This is not cowardice; it is the behavior of someone who understands the system she is operating within. Her grasp of court protocol is about to be turned to creative strategic use: the same laws that threatened her also provided the mechanism for Haman's downfall.</p>",
        "11": "<p>'Anyone — man or woman — who enters the king's inner court without being summoned has but one law: death, unless the king extends the golden scepter.' Herodotus (3.118, 140) and Ctesias both confirm this Persian court protocol: unauthorized entry to the king's presence was a capital offense. The thirty-day gap since Esther had last been summoned was significant: it indicated either a cooling of the king's interest or a protocol oversight. Her analysis of the risk was legally accurate.</p>",
        "12": "<p>The reporting of Esther's words back to Mordecai maintains the messenger chain — the same indirect communication structure used throughout this chapter. The narrative slows to show every step of the communication across the palace-harem boundary, emphasizing both the physical separation and the moral gap Esther must bridge. Each relay of the message is an opportunity for distortion or delay; the fact that the communication is preserved intact signals the narrator's interest in precision: these words matter.</p>",
        "13": "<p>Mordecai's reply — '<strong>Do not think in your heart that you will escape among all the Jews because you are in the king's house</strong>' — is a warning about false security. The same logic that had protected Esther (her hidden identity, her palace position) would not protect her if the genocide was implemented: the decree applied to 'all Jews' (3:13), and Esther's identity would eventually be exposed. Mordecai appealed to her survival instinct before appealing to her responsibility — meeting her first concern (her own safety) head-on rather than dismissing it.</p>",
        "14": "<p>'<strong>For if you remain completely silent at this critical time, relief and deliverance will come to the Jews from another place</strong> (<em>māqôm</em>), but you and your father's house will perish. And who knows whether you have not come to the kingdom for such a time as this?' The word <em>māqôm</em> (place) is used as a Jewish euphemism for God in later rabbinic literature; here it operates as a veiled divine reference consistent with the book's literary strategy of never naming God directly. Mordecai does not question whether deliverance will come — only whether Esther will be its instrument. 'Such a time as this' (<em>kāʿēṯ kāzōʾṯ</em>) is the book's central theological claim: providence has positioned Esther at exactly the right moment.</p>",
        "15": "<p>Esther's decision is signaled by her initiative: she 'sent this reply to Mordecai' — shifting from passive respondent to active commander. The change in her posture from 'I cannot' to 'Go, gather' is the pivot of the book. Her instruction to gather the Jews in Susa for a three-day fast activated the community's communal resources of prayer and intercession. This is the only act in the entire book that approximates prayer: the fast before entering the king's presence is the closest the narrative comes to directly invoking divine assistance, doing so through community practice of fasting rather than explicit petition.</p>",
        "16": "<p>'<strong>If I perish, I perish</strong>' (<em>wəkaʾăšer āḇaḏtî āḇāḏtî</em>) echoes Ruth's declaration of covenant commitment: 'where you go I will go… where you die I will die' (Ruth 1:16–17). Both statements express total commitment by accepting the worst possible outcome rather than retreating to safety. Esther's acceptance of personal risk is framed not as heroism but as covenant logic: the community's survival outweighs personal safety. The three-day fast mirrors other biblical three-day periods of crisis and transformation (Jonah 1:17; Hos 6:2).</p>",
        "17": "<p>'Mordecai went away and did everything Esther had commanded him' — the reversal of authority is complete. The protector who had directed the orphaned girl throughout the book now follows her instructions. The verb 'commanded' (<em>ṣiwwāh</em>, H6680) is used for binding commands of authority — the same verb used for God commanding Noah (Gen 6:22) and Moses commanding Israel. Esther has moved from ward to commander; the crisis has transformed her social role from protected to protector, from receiver of guidance to giver of it.</p>"
    },
    "5": {
        "1": "<p>Esther 'put on her royal robes (<em>malkûṯ</em>) and stood in the inner court of the palace, facing the king's hall.' The royal robes were both personal adornment and a statement of identity: she appeared as queen, not as a Jewish woman. The inner court was the zone requiring the king's scepter permission — her standing there was already an act of potentially capital civil disobedience. The three-day fast (4:16) had ended. The detail that she 'put on' royal identity mirrors Mordecai's earlier refusal to 'put on' the clothes Esther sent (4:4) — clothing as a form of strategic self-presentation.</p>",
        "2": "<p>The king extended the <strong>golden scepter</strong> (<em>šarḇîṭ hazzāhāḇ</em>) — the single most important act in the narrative to this point. Persian court protocol, confirmed by Herodotus (3.118), required the king's explicit signal of acceptance before an unsummoned visitor could approach. The golden scepter was both an instrument of office and a symbol of the king's mercy. The text records that Esther 'found favor in his eyes' (<em>wattīśāʾ ḥēn bəʿênāyw</em>) — the same favor formula used at every stage of her advancement (2:9, 15, 17). Divine favor, working through human attraction, continues its pattern.</p>",
        "3": "<p>'What is the matter, Queen Esther? What is your request? It shall be granted to you, even to half the kingdom.' The 'half the kingdom' formula is a hyperbolic expression of royal generosity common in the ancient Near East (cf. Mk 6:23 — Herod's identical offer to Salome). It signals that the king was pleased and disposed to grant requests. The formula recurs at 5:6 and 7:2, creating a structural pattern: Esther has repeated opportunities to make her petition, building suspense and establishing the king's explicit openness before she reveals the full weight of her request.</p>",
        "4": "<p>Esther's answer — 'let the king and Haman come today to the banquet I have prepared' — is a masterwork of diplomatic indirection. Instead of immediately presenting her life-or-death petition, she invited the king to a banquet. The delay has been analyzed as (a) strategic psychology: building trust and intimacy before the difficult request; (b) tactical positioning: getting Haman into a controlled setting; (c) divine providence: the banquet delay allowed Haman's gallows-building (v14) and the king's sleepless night (6:1) to intervene. Persian banquet diplomacy was well understood: the table created a context of intimacy and obligation.</p>",
        "5": "<p>The king's immediate response — 'Bring Haman at once' — shows both his eagerness to please Esther and his continued trust in Haman. Haman and the king sharing the queen's private banquet was an honor of the highest order — access to the royal household at a level reserved for the inner circle. The banquet is the social setting within which the crisis will be resolved: the book began with a banquet (ch. 1), reached its crisis over drinks (3:15), and will reach its resolution through a banquet where Haman's evil is exposed (7:1–6).</p>",
        "6": "<p>At the wine banquet, the king repeated the 'half the kingdom' offer. The setting — a private banquet with wine — is the most intimate social context the Persian court offered; it mirrored the setting in which Ahasuerus had drunkenly sent for Vashti (1:10–11). The parallel is deliberate: the first queen refused to appear before a drunk king; the second queen orchestrated her appearance before a sober king at a strategic moment. The wine in ch. 1 led to Vashti's fall; the wine in ch. 5 will enable Esther's request to be heard in a favorable context.</p>",
        "7": "<p>Esther's answer — 'My petition and my request—' — is notably incomplete as the text records it. She begins and then redirects. This rhetorical suspension builds maximum suspense for the reader while in the narrative it reflects Esther's tactical decision to delay her petition one more day. Whether this was strategic calculation, divine guidance, or sensing that the time was not yet right, the effect is the same: the petition is deferred, and in the deferral space, Haman builds his gallows and the king cannot sleep. Providence uses delay as its instrument.</p>",
        "8": "<p>Esther's offer of a second banquet — 'if it pleases the king to grant my petition and fulfill my request, let the king and Haman come tomorrow to the banquet I will prepare for them' — completed the deferral strategy. The explicit linking of the banquet invitation with her unspecified petition built anticipation: the king now knew something significant was coming. The word 'please' (<em>ṭôḇ ʿal hammelek</em>) is the same formula used throughout the book for royal approval — Esther was working the protocol of royal pleasure at every level simultaneously.</p>",
        "9": "<p>Haman 'left that day glad and in high spirits.' His joy at the double invitation was the peak of his social ascent. The cruelest irony of the book is concentrated in this verse: Haman's greatest social triumph immediately precedes his encounter with Mordecai at the gate, which left him 'filled with rage' (<em>wayyimlāʾ ʿal-mordəḵay ḥēmāh</em>). The smallest slight — one man refusing to stand or bow — cancels all the honor of royal dining. His inability to separate his good fortune from one person's non-compliance characterizes his self-destructive obsession.</p>",
        "10": "<p>Haman 'controlled himself (<em>wayyiṯʾapaq</em>, H662 — to restrain oneself)' and went home to boast of his honors. The self-restraint is temporary and thin: his gathering of 'his friends and his wife Zeresh' for a boasting session suggests he needed external validation to manage the wound of Mordecai's refusal. Zeresh is one of the few named women in the book besides Esther and Vashti; her counsel in v14 mirrors the male counselors' pattern — women as influential advisers in the Persian court setting, consistent with what is known of Persian royal households.</p>",
        "11": "<p>Haman's boast covered 'his enormous wealth, his many sons (<em>rōḇ bānāyw</em>, 9:7–10 will name ten sons), and all the ways the king had honored him — how he had elevated him above the other officials and royal servants.' The three categories — wealth, progeny, and honor — represent the fullness of human flourishing in the ancient Near Eastern worldview. The book's implicit theology of reversal will systematically strip each category from him: his sons will be killed (9:7–10), his honor will be given to Mordecai, and his wealth will go to Esther (8:1).</p>",
        "12": "<p>'Furthermore, Queen Esther invited no one but me to accompany the king to the banquet she gave. And tomorrow also I am invited by her along with the king.' The private royal banquet access — the pinnacle of social honor in the Persian court — is what Haman is most proud of. His citation of this honor alongside his wealth and sons reflects the honor-shame culture of the ancient Near East: social recognition by the highest authority was the ultimate measure of a man's worth. His identity was entirely constructed from external validation, which is why Mordecai's refusal was existentially unbearable.</p>",
        "13": "<p>'But none of this satisfies me (<em>ʾênennî šōweh lî</em> — 'it is not worth anything to me') as long as I see Mordecai the Jew sitting at the king's gate.' The confession of inner emptiness despite external success is one of the most honest moments in the book. Haman himself acknowledged that his honors were worthless in the presence of the one witness who would not affirm them. The psychology of resentment — where one relationship of non-recognition nullifies all other affirmations — anticipates Jesus's identification of seeking honor from men rather than from God as the root of spiritual blindness (John 5:44).</p>",
        "14": "<p>Zeresh and friends advised the construction of a <strong>gallows fifty cubits high</strong> (~75 feet) — an enormous structure designed for maximum public visibility. The advice to 'speak to the king in the morning' reflects an understanding of court timing: morning petitions, before the day's business crowded the king's attention, were more likely to succeed. The gallows construction is the action that generates the book's central irony: Haman builds the instrument of his own execution. Ancient audiences would have recognized the motif of the schemer trapped by his own scheme — wisdom literature's classic pattern (Ps 7:15; Prov 26:27).</p>"
    }
}


def main():
    c = load_comm('mkt-context', 'esther')
    merge_comm(c, EST15)
    save_comm('mkt-context', 'esther', c)
    count = sum(len(v) for v in EST15.values())
    print(f'esther mkt-context: wrote {count} verses for ch 1–5')


if __name__ == '__main__':
    main()
